    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-01-26T12:31:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-01-26T12:31:00-05:00" n="337"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d337">
                <head>337. Message From the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff (<persName
                        corresp="#p_MTH_1">Moorer</persName>) to Certain Commanders<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d337fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 218, Records of the Chairman, Records of
                            <persName corresp="#p_MTH_1">Thomas Moorer</persName>, Box 69, <gloss
                            target="#t_JCS_1">JCS</gloss> Out General Service Messages, January
                        1973. Top Secret; Immediate; <gloss target="#t_Specat_1">Specat</gloss>;
                        Exclusive.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1973-01-26T17:31:00+00:00">January 26, 1973,
                        1731Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>9125. For Admiral <persName corresp="#p_GNAM_1">Gayler</persName>, General
                        <persName corresp="#p_MJC_1">Meyer</persName>, General <persName
                        corresp="#p_WFC_1">Weyand</persName>, General <persName corresp="#p_VJW_1"
                        >Vogt</persName>, Admiral <persName corresp="#p_CBA_1">Clarey</persName>,
                    General <persName corresp="#p_CLD_1">Clay</persName>, Admiral <persName
                        corresp="#p_HJL_1">Holloway</persName> and Admiral <persName
                        corresp="#p_CDW_1">Cooper</persName>.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Subj_1">Subj</gloss>: Air Operations/Ceasefire/<gloss
                        target="#t_POW_1">POW</gloss>s.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>During the next sixty days the most important single event will be the
                        return of our prisoners of war. Parenthetically I would also add that
                        possession of our <gloss target="#t_POW_1">POW</gloss>’s is the only
                        leverage the <gloss target="#t_NVN_1">NVN</gloss> have. Therefore, it is
                        absolutely mandatory that we conduct our air operations in such a manner
                        that there will be no cause to overfly <gloss target="#t_NVN_1">NVN</gloss>
                        territory or deliver ordnance against targets in <gloss target="#t_NVN_1"
                            >NVN</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>I have resisted the idea of a buffer zone along the Laos-<gloss
                            target="#t_NVN_1">NVN</gloss> border because whatever distance we
                        specify it will be either too much or too little depending on the
                        circumstances. Consequently our pilots must understand the situation and
                        conduct themselves accordingly. We cannot permit advertent or inadvertent
                        violations of the <gloss target="#t_NVN_1">NVN</gloss> border which might
                        slow down the return of our <gloss target="#t_POW_1">POW</gloss>s.</item>
                    <pb facs="1217" n="1174" xml:id="pg_1174"/>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>At this time and under the present circumstances there are no targets in
                        Laos adjacent to the <gloss target="#t_NVN_1">NVN</gloss> border that are so
                        important we can risk border violations or get ourselves in a position where
                        we must take overt action against targets in <gloss target="#t_NVN_1"
                            >NVN</gloss>. Therefore, air operations near the Laos-<gloss
                            target="#t_NVN_1">NVN</gloss> border will be planned and executed in
                        such a way as to preclude overflight or the necessity for protective
                        reaction. We simply cannot afford any mistakes.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Warm regards.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
